Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1491–":"1491–Deceased","1491–Male":"1491–Deceased","1490–1550":"1490–1550","1504–1568":"1504–1568","1504–Female":"1504–Deceased","1464–1530":"1464–1530","1468–1530":"1468–1530","1550":"1550","1491":"1491","1490":"1490","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1468":"1468","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","1464":"1464","1505":"1505","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Auder","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Markus, Otto.","German: from a short form of a personal name, <i>Botthar</i>, formed with Old High German <i>biutan</i> ‘to bid or command’ or <i>boto</i> ‘messenger’.","German: variant of   Buder  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Buder","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Manfred.  Jewish Aron, Dorit.","German: variant of   Budner  .","German: in Swabia, a nickname for a bully, from <i>Buder</i> or <i>Bauder</i> ‘stroke, blow’, from Middle High German <i>buden</i> ‘to hit’."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":58,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":67,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":78,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705207,"age":94,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, 